    <fr:title text="Algebraic Theory of an endofunction with a fixed point">Algebraic Theory of an endofunction with a fixed point</fr:title>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <html:p>The algebraic theory of an endofunction with a fixed point consists of two operations</html:p>
    <html:ol><html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta (1)]]></fr:tex></html:li>
<html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega (0)]]></fr:tex></html:li></html:ol>
    <html:p>satisfying one equation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta (\Omega ) = \Omega ]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
    <html:p>A computational intuition is that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta (x)]]></fr:tex> is an internal computation step and that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega ]]></fr:tex> is a diverging computation.</html:p>
    <html:p>The free algebra on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> can be explicitly described as having underlying set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(\mathbb {N}\times  X) \uplus  \{\Omega \}]]></fr:tex>, i.e. an intensional computation either terminates with a result after some finite number of steps, or it diverges.</html:p>
  </fr:mainmatter>
