            <fr:title text="Delay Monad on Set">Delay Monad on Set</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>The Delay monad on Sets is given by the final coalgebra <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D X = X \uplus  D X]]></fr:tex>. This is monad used as a simple model of programs that may diverge where the number of "steps" is observable.</html:p>
            <html:p>An explicit construction of the Delay monad can be given by <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[D X = \{f : \mathbb {N} \rightharpoonup  X \uplus  1 | f(n) = \textrm {inl}(x) \Rightarrow  f(n+1) = \textrm {inl}(x) ]]></fr:tex> in other words, monotone functions from the natural numbers to the maybe monad on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> where the maybe monad is given the ordering that adjoins a bottom element to a discrete order.</html:p>
            <html:p>The delay monad can be given an inductive characterization as the free <fr:link href="/MYZG/" title="Algebraic Theory of an endofunction with a fixed point" uri="https://um-catlab.github.io/MYZG/" display-uri="MYZG" type="local">fixed point algebra</fr:link> if and only if Markov's principle holds. Without Markov's principle, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[DX]]></fr:tex> can be given the structure of a fixed point algebra but we cannot prove it is free.</html:p>
            <html:p>In fact, the delay monad is finitary (and thus the free algebras for an <fr:link href="/L94N/" title="Finitary Algebraic Theory" uri="https://um-catlab.github.io/L94N/" display-uri="L94N" type="local">algebraic theory</fr:link>) if and only if Markov's principle holds. Therefore if the delay monad is finitary then it is the free fixed point algebra.</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
